South Africa&#8217;s private sector credit demand growth slowed to 4.95% year-on-year in March from a revised 5.29% in February, central bank data showed on Friday.Expansion in the broadly defined M3 measure of money supply fell to 5.62% from a revised 6.62%.Nedbank has issued the following statement: &#8220;Growth in credit demand is expected to remain depressed in the next few months as both households and corporates take a wait and see approach with regards to the trajectory of the rand and therefore to inflation and interest rates. The current political environment will also serve to keep confidence low, which does not bode well for credit demand. However, for technical reasons around the treatment of African Bank s loans, there will be a one or two percentage point lift to credit on a year-on-year basis from April.&#8221;